10022 |pmid=18056796 }} [http://psp.sagepub.com/content/34/2/159.full.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sexisthumor2\">{{cite journal | last1= Viki | first1= G. Tendayi | last2= Thomae | first2= Manuela | last3= Cullen | first3= Amy | last4= Fernandez | first4= Hannah | title= The effect of sexist humor and type of rape on men's self-reported rape proclivity and victim blame | journal= Current Research in Social Psychology | date= December 16, 2007 | volume= 13 | issue= 10 | pages= 122\u2013132 | url= https://www.academia.edu/266974 | accessdate= October 16, 2013 }} [http://www.uiowa.edu/~grpproc/crisp/crisp13_10.pdf Pdf.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229144501/http://www.uiowa.edu/~grpproc/crisp/crisp13_10.pdf |date=December 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sexsegregation\">{{cite journal|last=Charles|first=Maria|title=Deciphering sex segregation: vertical and horizontal inequalities in ten national labor markets|journal=Acta Sociologica|date=December 2003|volume= 46|issue=4|series=No. 4|pages=267\u2013287|doi=10.1177/0001699303464001}} [http://asj.sagepub.com/content/46/4/267.full.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"timeline2\">{{cite web|last=Imbornoni|first=Ann-Marie|title=Timeline of key events in the American women's rights movement 1921\u20131979 |url=http://www.infoplease.com/spot/womenstimeline2.html|work=Information Please Database|publisher=Pearson Education, Inc.|accessdate=October 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"timeline3\">{{cite web|last=Imbornoni|first=Ann-Marie|title=Timeline of key events in the American women's rights movement 1980-present |url=http://www.infoplease.com/spot/womenstimeline3.html|work=Information Please Database|publisher=Pearson Education, Inc.|accessdate=October 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"trans healthcare\">{{cite web|last=Grant |first=Jaime |title=National transgender discrimination survey report on health and health care |url=http://transequality.org/PDFs/NTDSReportonHealth_final.pdf |publisher=National Center for Transgender Equality and the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force |accessdate=March 21, 2014 |display-authors=etal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407204726/http://transequality.org/PDFs/NTDSReportonHealth_final.pdf |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\nSocial Politics, Oxford University Press, Marie Evertsson, 2009, pp.&nbsp;210\u2013241\n\n==External links==\n* [http://genderreport.com/2013/02/28/new-report-documents-persistent-gender-inequalities-in-u-s-media/ New report documents persistent gender inequalities in U.S. media]\n\n{{Women's rights in the United States}}\n{{North America topic|prefix=Gender inequality in|state=expanded|countries_only=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Gender in the United States|Inequality]]\n[[Category:Gender inequality in the United States|*]]\n[[Category:Women's rights in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "27.125.189.15", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHispanic or Latino)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gender_inequality_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Chicago Cultural Center", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = November 2019}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Chicago Public Library, Central Building\n| nrhp_type = nrhp\n| designated_other1_name = Chicago Landmark\n| designated_other1_date = November 15, 1976<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webapps.cityofchicago.org/LandmarksWeb/landmarkDetail.do?lanID=1274|title=Chicago Public Library/Cultural Center|publisher=City of Chicago Dept. of Pl. and Devpmt., Landmarks Div.|year=2003|accessdate=2007-08-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080613044114/http://webapps.cityofchicago.org/LandmarksWeb/landmarkDetail.do?lanID=1274|archivedate=2008-06-13}}</ref>\n| designated_other1_abbr = CL\n| designated_other1_link = Chicago Landmark\n| designated_other1_color = #aaccff\n| image = Chicago Cultural Center and Chicago Public Library, Chicago June 30, 2012-42.jpg\n| caption = Chicago Cultural Center\n| location = 78 E. Washington St.,<br/>[[Chicago, IL]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|53|2|N|87|37|30|W|display=inline,title}}\n| built = 1893\n| architect = C. A. Coolidge, Robert C. Spencer\n| architecture =\n| added = July 31, 1972\n| refnum = 72000449 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n| locmapin = United States Chicago Central#Illinois#USA\n}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | direction         = vertical\n | header_align      = center\n | header            = [[Preston Bradley]] Hall and Tiffany dome\n<!--image 1-->\n | image1            = 11-1338-dome-library-chicago.jpg\n | alt1              = [[Preston Bradley]] Hall\n | caption1          = [[Preston Bradley]] Hall\n<!--image 1-->\n | image2            = 11-1337-dome-library-chicago.jpg\n | alt2              = Tiffany glass dome\n | caption2          = Tiffany glass dome\n}}\n\nThe '''Chicago Cultural Center,''' opened in 1897, is a [[Chicago Landmark]] building operated by Chicago's Department of Cultural Affairs and Special Events that houses the city's official reception venue where the [[Mayor of Chicago|Mayor]] of [[Chicago]] has welcomed Presidents and royalty, diplomats and community leaders. It is located in the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]], across [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] from [[Millennium Park]].  Originally the central library building, it was converted in 1977 to an arts and culture center at the instigation of Commissioner of Cultural Affairs [[Lois Weisberg]]. The city's central library is now housed across the Loop in the spacious, [[Postmodern architecture|postmodern]] [[Harold Washington Library Center]] opened in 1991.\n\nAs the nation's first free municipal cultural center, the Chicago Cultural Center is one of the city's most [[Tourism in Chicago|popular attractions]] and is considered one of the most comprehensive arts showcases in the [[United States]]. Each year, the Chicago Cultural Center features more than 1,000 programs and exhibitions covering a wide range of the performing, visual and literary arts. It also serves as headquarters for the [[Chicago Children's Choir]]. MB Real Estate provides events management for the center.\n\n==Architecture of the Chicago Cultural Center==\nThe building was designed by Boston architectural firm [[Shepley, Rutan and Coolidge]] for the city's central library, and [[Grand Army of the Republic]] (GAR) meeting hall and memorial in 1892.  The land was donated by the GAR and the building was completed in 1897 at a cost of nearly $2 million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|2|1897|r=2}} million in {{Inflation-year|US}}). It is organized as a 4-story north wing (77 East Randolph entrance) and a 5-story south wing (78 East Washington entrance), 104 feet tall, with {{convert|3|ft|m|adj=mid|-thick}} masonry walls faced with [[Indiana Limestone|Bedford Blue Limestone]] on a granite base, and designed in a generally [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] style with Italian Renaissance elements. It is capped with two stained-glass domes, set symmetrically atop the two wings. Key points of architectural interest are as follows:\n\n* Randolph Street entrance and stairway - Entrance with [[doric column]]s, mahogany doors, and entry hall with [[coffered ceiling]] and walls of green-veined [[Vermont]] marble. The curving stairway is faced with Knoxville pink marble, and features mosaics and ornate bronze balusters.\n* Washington Street entrance, lobby, and grand staircase - Arched portal, bronze-framed doors, and a 3-story, vaulted lobby with walls of white [[Carrara]] marble and mosaics. The staircase is also of white Carrara marble, set with medallions of green marble from [[Connemara]], [[Ireland]], and intricate mosaics of [[Favrile]] glass, stone, and mother of pearl. The stairway to the 5th floor was inspired by [[Venice]]'s [[Bridge of Sighs]].\n* [[Grand Army of the Republic]] Memorial - A large hall and rotunda in the north wing. The hall is faced with deep green [[Vermont]] marble, broken by a series of arches for windows and mahogany doors. The rotunda features 30-foot walls of Knoxville pink marble, mosaic floor, and a fine, stained-glass dome in [[Renaissance]] pattern by the firm of Healy and Millet.\n* Sidney R. Yates Gallery - replica of an assembly hall in the [[Doge's Palace, Venice|Doge's Palace]], [[Venice]], with heavily ornamented [[pilaster]]s and coffered ceiling.\n* [[Preston Bradley]] Hall - A large, ornately patterned room of curving white Carrara marble, capped with an austere 38-foot [[Louis Comfort Tiffany|Tiffany]] glass dome designed by artist [[Jacob Adolphus Holzer|J. A. Holzer]]. The Cultural Center states this to be the largest Tiffany dome in the world.\n\n==Past exhibitions==\n''Crossroads: Modernism in Ukraine, 1910-1930'' was a display of art by Ukrainian artists, such as Sukher Ber Rybak, Vsevolod Maskymovych, and Oleksandr Bohomazov to name a few.  ''Crossroads'' was organized by the [[Foundation for International Arts and Education]] with the [[National Art Museum of Ukraine]].  It is presented by the Chicago Department of Cultural Affairs and the Kyiv Committee of the Chicago Sister Cities International Program.  The exhibition ran from July 22, 2006 - October 15, 2006.\n\n== \"Rush More\" ==\nIn 2017, [[Kerry James Marshall]] was commissioned to produce the inaugural mural entitled \u201cRush More\u201d. Located on the west fa\u00e7ade of the cultural center, the piece was intended to be an homage to women who have contributed to the culture of Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peoriapublicradio.org/post/new-chicago-mural-honors-influential-women|title=New Chicago Mural Honors Influential Women|last=Press|first=Associated|website=www.peoriapublicradio.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\nPortrayed are:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* Cheryl Lynn Bruce\n* Jacqueline Russell\n* Maggie Daley\n* Margaret Burroughs\n* Monica Haslip\n* [[Oprah Winfrey]]\n* [[Gwendolyn Brooks]]\n* [[Lois Weisburg]]\n* [[Sandra Delgado]]\n* [[Achy Obejas]]\n* [[Abena Joan Brown]]\n* [[Harriet Monroe]]\n* Jackie Taylor\n* [[Barbara Gaines (director)|Barbara Gaines]]\n* Susanne Ghez\n* [[Joan Gray]]\n* [[Ruth Page (activist)|Ruth Page]]\n* [[Sandra Cisneros]]\n* [[Barbara Jones-Hogu]]\n* Jane Saks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/chicago/news/take-a-look-at-kerry-james-marshalls-gigantic-new-mural-at-the-chicago-cultural-center-120417|title=Take a look at Kerry James Marshall\u2019s gigantic new mural at the Chicago Cultural Center|website=Time Out Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n}}\n\nWashington painted the mural on a scale rendering of the building. The piece was then transposed to the actual fa\u00e7ade by the muralist Jeff Zimmerman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/418787/kerry-james-marshall-mural-chicago/|title=Kerry James Marshall's Largest Work Yet Honors Women in the Arts|date=2017-12-28|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> Financing for the project was made possible by the non-profit, Murals of Acceptance and through philanthropic donations from [[David Arquette]], [[Patricia Arquette]], [[Marc Benioff]], and Lynne Benioff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-kerry-james-marshall-mural-unveiled-chicago-1204-story.html|title=Giant mural by Kerry James Marshall honors Chicago women of culture|last=Johnson|first=Steve|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Chicago architecture]]\n* [[List of museums and cultural institutions in Chicago]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.chicagoculturalcenter.org}}\n*High-resolution 360\u00b0 Panoramas and Images of [https://mcid.mcah.columbia.edu/art-atlas/modern-architecture-chicago/chicago-cultural-center Chicago Cultural Center | Art Atlas]\n{{Chicago Loop}}\n{{Chicago Landmark cultural venues}}\n{{Chicago Landmark municipal}}\n{{Chicago mci}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Central Chicago]]\n[[Category:Cultural centers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Culture of Chicago]]\n[[Category:Grand Army of the Republic]]\n[[Category:Chicago Landmarks]]\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1897]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Former library buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Libraries on the National Register of Historic Places in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Chicago]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = November 2019}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Chicago Public Library, Central Building\n| nrhp_type = nrhp\n| designated_other1_name = Chicago Landmark\n| designated_other1_date = November 15, 1976<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webapps.cityofchicago.org/LandmarksWeb/landmarkDetail.do?lanID=1274|title=Chicago Public Library/Cultural Center|publisher=City of Chicago Dept. of Pl. and Devpmt., Landmarks Div.|year=2003|accessdate=2007-08-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080613044114/http://webapps.cityofchicago.org/LandmarksWeb/landmarkDetail.do?lanID=1274|archivedate=2008-06-13}}</ref>\n| designated_other1_abbr = CL\n| designated_other1_link = Chicago Landmark\n| designated_other1_color = #aaccff\n| image = Chicago Cultural Center and Chicago Public Library, Chicago June 30, 2012-42.jpg\n| caption = Chicago Cultural Center\n| location = 78 E. Washington St.,<br/>[[Chicago, IL]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|53|2|N|87|37|30|W|display=inline,title}}\n| built = 1893\n| architect = C. A. Coolidge, Robert C. Spencer\n| architecture =\n| added = July 31, 1972\n| refnum = 72000449 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n| locmapin = United States Chicago Central#Illinois#USA\n}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | direction         = vertical\n | header_align      = center\n | header            = [[Preston Bradley]] Hall and Tiffany dome\n<!--image 1-->\n | image1            = 11-1338-dome-library-chicago.jpg\n | alt1              = [[Preston Bradley]] Hall\n | caption1          = [[Preston Bradley]] Hall\n<!--image 1-->\n | image2            = 11-1337-dome-library-chicago.jpg\n | alt2              = Tiffany glass dome\n | caption2          = Tiffany glass dome\n}}\n\nThe '''Chicago Cultural Center,''' opened in 1897, is a [[Chicago Landmark]] building operated by Chicago's Department of Cultural Affairs and Special Events that houses the city's official reception venue where the [[Mayor of Chicago|Mayor]] of [[Chicago]] has welcomed Presidents and royalty, diplomats and community leaders. It is located in the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]], across [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] from [[Millennium Park]].  Originally the central library building, it was converted in 1977 to an arts and culture center at the instigation of Commissioner of Cultural Affairs [[Lois Weisberg]]. The city's central library is now housed across the Loop in the spacious, [[Postmodern architecture|postmodern]] [[Harold Washington Library Center]] opened in 1991.\n\nAs the nation's first free municipal cultural center, the Chicago Cultural Center is one of the city's most [[Tourism in Chicago|popular attractions]] and is considered one of the most comprehensive arts showcases in the [[United States]]. Each year, the Chicago Cultural Center features more than 1,000 programs and exhibitions covering a wide range of the performing, visual and literary arts. It also serves as headquarters for the [[Chicago Children's Choir]]. MB Real Estate provides events management for the center. \n\n==Architecture of the Chicago Cultural Center==\nThe building was designed by Boston architectural firm [[Shepley, Rutan and Coolidge]] for the city's central library, and [[Grand Army of the Republic]] (GAR) meeting hall and memorial in 1892.  The land was donated by the GAR and the building was completed in 1897 at a cost of nearly $2 million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|2|1897|r=2}} million in {{Inflation-year|US}}). It is organized as a 4-story north wing (77 East Randolph entrance) and a 5-story south wing (78 East Washington entrance), 104 feet tall, with {{convert|3|ft|m|adj=mid|-thick}} masonry walls faced with [[Indiana Limestone|Bedford Blue Limestone]] on a granite base, and designed in a generally [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] style with Italian Renaissance elements. It is capped with two stained-glass domes, set symmetrically atop the two wings. Key points of architectural interest are as follows:\n\n* Randolph Street entrance and stairway - Entrance with [[doric column]]s, mahogany doors, and entry hall with [[coffered ceiling]] and walls of green-veined [[Vermont]] marble. The curving stairway is faced with Knoxville pink marble, and features mosaics and ornate bronze balusters.\n* Washington Street entrance, lobby, and grand staircase - Arched portal, bronze-framed doors, and a 3-story, vaulted lobby with walls of white [[Carrara]] marble and mosaics. The staircase is also of white Carrara marble, set with medallions of green marble from [[Connemara]], [[Ireland]], and intricate mosaics of [[Favrile]] glass, stone, and mother of pearl. The stairway to the 5th floor was inspired by [[Venice]]'s [[Bridge of Sighs]].\n* [[Grand Army of the Republic]] Memorial - A large hall and rotunda in the north wing. The hall is faced with deep green [[Vermont]] marble, broken by a series of arches for windows and mahogany doors. The rotunda features 30-foot walls of Knoxville pink marble, mosaic floor, and a fine, stained-glass dome in [[Renaissance]] pattern by the firm of Healy and Millet.\n* Sidney R. Yates Gallery - replica of an assembly hall in the [[Doge's Palace, Venice|Doge's Palace]], [[Venice]], with heavily ornamented [[pilaster]]s and coffered ceiling.\n* [[Preston Bradley]] Hall - A large, ornately patterned room of curving white Carrara marble, capped with an austere 38-foot [[Louis Comfort Tiffany|Tiffany]] glass dome designed by artist [[Jacob Adolphus Holzer|J. A. Holzer]]. The Cultural Center states this to be the largest Tiffany dome in the world.\n\n==Past exhibitions==\n''Crossroads: Modernism in Ukraine, 1910-1930'' was a display of art by Ukrainian artists, such as Sukher Ber Rybak, Vsevolod Maskymovych, and Oleksandr Bohomazov to name a few.  ''Crossroads'' was organized by the [[Foundation for International Arts and Education]] with the [[National Art Museum of Ukraine]].  It is presented by the Chicago Department of Cultural Affairs and the Kyiv Committee of the Chicago Sister Cities International Program.  The exhibition ran from July 22, 2006 - October 15, 2006.\n\n== \"Rush More\" ==\nIn 2017, [[Kerry James Marshall]] was commissioned to produce the inaugural mural entitled \u201cRush More\u201d. Located on the west fa\u00e7ade of the cultural center, the piece was intended to be an homage to women who have contributed to the culture of Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peoriapublicradio.org/post/new-chicago-mural-honors-influential-women|title=New Chicago Mural Honors Influential Women|last=Press|first=Associated|website=www.peoriapublicradio.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> \n\nPortrayed are:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* Cheryl Lynn Bruce\n* Jacqueline Russell\n* Maggie Daley\n* Margaret Burroughs\n* Monica Haslip\n* [[Oprah Winfrey]]\n* [[Gwendolyn Brooks]]\n* [[Lois Weisburg]]\n* [[Sandra Delgado]]\n* [[Achy Obejas]]\n* [[Abena Joan Brown]]\n* [[Harriet Monroe]]\n* Jackie Taylor\n* [[Barbara Gaines (director)|Barbara Gaines]]\n* Susanne Ghez\n* [[Joan Gray]]\n* [[Ruth Page (activist)|Ruth Page]]\n* [[Sandra Cisneros]]\n* [[Barbara Jones-Hogu]]\n* Jane Saks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/chicago/news/take-a-look-at-kerry-james-marshalls-gigantic-new-mural-at-the-chicago-cultural-center-120417|title=Take a look at Kerry James Marshall\u2019s gigantic new mural at the Chicago Cultural Center|website=Time Out Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n}}\n\nWashington painted the mural on a scale rendering of the building. The piece was then transposed to the actual fa\u00e7ade by the muralist Jeff Zimmerman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/418787/kerry-james-marshall-mural-chicago/|title=Kerry James Marshall's Largest Work Yet Honors Women in the Arts|date=2017-12-28|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> Financing for the project was made possible by the non-profit, Murals of Acceptance and through philanthropic donations from [[David Arquette]], [[Patricia Arquette]], [[Marc Benioff]], and Lynne Benioff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-kerry-james-marshall-mural-unveiled-chicago-1204-story.html|title=Giant mural by Kerry James Marshall honors Chicago women of culture|last=Johnson|first=Steve|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Chicago architecture]]\n* [[List of museums and cultural institutions in Chicago]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.chicagoculturalcenter.org}}\n*High-resolution 360\u00b0 Panoramas and Images of [https://mcid.mcah.columbia.edu/art-atlas/modern-architecture-chicago/chicago-cultural-center Chicago Cultural Center | Art Atlas]\n{{Chicago Loop}}\n{{Chicago Landmark cultural venues}}\n{{Chicago Landmark municipal}}\n{{Chicago mci}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Central Chicago]]\n[[Category:Cultural centers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Culture of Chicago]]\n[[Category:Grand Army of the Republic]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1897]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Former library buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Libraries on the National Register of Historic Places in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Chicago]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Cultural_Center"}
