    = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -4\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_ft                    = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|40|25|15|N|80|5|20|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]s\n| postal_code                     = \n| area_code                       = \n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 42-66320\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = \n| website                         = [http://rosslynfarmspa.com/ Rosslyn Farms Community Club]\n[http://rosslynfarms.net/ Rosslyn Farms Borough]\n| footnotes                       = \n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| population_est                  = 415\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_total_km2                  = 1.45\n| area_land_km2                   = 1.45\n| area_water_km2                  = 0.00\n| population_density_km2          = 286.14\n}}\n\n'''Rosslyn Farms''' is a suburban borough located {{convert|5|mi|0}} west of [[Pittsburgh]] in [[Allegheny County, Pennsylvania]] in the United States. It is a small community, with an area of only {{convert|0.6|sqmi}}.  The population was 427 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=https://www.census.gov| title=Race, Hispanic or Latino, Age, and Housing Occupancy: 2010 Census Redistricting Data (Public Law 94-171) Summary File (QT-PL), Rosslyn Farms borough, Pennsylvania| publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]| accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding and adjacent communities==\nRosslyn Farms is bordered by [[Carnegie, Pennsylvania|Carnegie]] to the south, [[Robinson Township, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Robinson Township]] to the west, and [[Thornburg, Pennsylvania|Thornburg]] to the north.  Chartiers Creek separates Rosslyn Farms from [[Crafton, Pennsylvania|Crafton]] to the east, the Pittsburgh neighborhood of [[East Carnegie (Pittsburgh)|East Carnegie]] to the southeast, and [[Scott Township, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Scott Township]] also to the southeast.\n\n==Geography==\nRosslyn Farms is located at 40\u00b025'15\" North, 80\u00b05'20\" West (40.420969, -80.088768).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the borough has a total area of {{convert|0.6|sqmi}}, all of it land.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1920= 315\n|1930= 334\n|1940= 432\n|1950= 448\n|1960= 555\n|1970= 608\n|1980= 521\n|1990= 483\n|2000= 464\n|2010= 427\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=415\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=Sources:<ref name=\"Census1930\">{{cite web|title=Number and Distribution of Inhabitants:Pennsylvania-Tennessee|url=http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/03815512v1ch09.pdf|work=Fifteenth Census|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref><ref name=\"Census1960\">{{cite web|title=Number of Inhabitants: Pennsylvania|url=http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/17216604v1p40ch02.pdf|work=18th Census of the United States|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Census1990\">{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania: Population and Housing Unit Counts|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/cen1990/cph2/cph-2-40.pdf|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref><ref name=\"CensusPopEst\">{{cite web|title=Annual Estimates of the Resident Population|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012-3.html|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=22 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019235623/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012-3.html|archivedate=19 October 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there are 464 people, 185 households, and 145 families residing in the borough.  The [[population density]] is 767.6 people per square mile (298.6/km\u00b2).  There are 193 housing units at an average density of 319.3 per square mile (124.2/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the borough is 99.14% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.65% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.00% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.00% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.00% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.00% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 0.22% from two or more races.  0.43% of the population are [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere are 185 households, out of which 30.3% have children under the age of 18 living with them, 71.4% are [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 3.8% have a female householder with no husband present, and 21.6% are non-families. 16.8% of all households are made up of individuals, and 5.9% have someone living alone who is 65 years of age or older.  The average household size is 2.51 and the average family size is 2.84.\n\nIn the borough the population is spread out, with 23.9% under the age of 18, 3.0% from 18 to 24, 26.9% from 25 to 44, 31.9% from 45 to 64, and 14.2% who are 65 years of age or older.  The median age is 44 years.  For every 100 females, there are 99.1 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there are 91.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the borough is $100,125, and the median income for a family is $145,799. Males have a median income of $105,327 versus $73,083 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the borough is $71,612.  5.8% of the population and 2.6% of families are below the [[poverty line]].  Out of the total population, 16.3% of those under the age of 18 and 0.0% of those 65 and older are living below the poverty line.\n\n\n== History ==\nFounded in 1902 by the Chartiers Land Company, Rosslyn Farms was developed by William Parrish.\n\nThe borough derives its name from [[Roslin, Midlothian|Roslin, Scotland]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=a4NIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G24DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7226%2C2342598 | title=Town names carry bit of history | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=May 10, 1984 | accessdate=31 October 2015 | author=Ackerman, Jan | pages=6}}</ref>\n\n==Government and Politics==\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential Elections Results'''<ref>{{cite web|last1=EL|title=2012 Allegheny County election|url=http://triblive.com/politics/2907065-74/pittsburgh-ward-hills-west-borough-braddock-east-elizabeth-north-park|website=Pittsburgh Tribune-Review|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=EL|title=2016 Pennsylvani general election...|url=http://newsinteractive.post-gazette.com/electionresultsgen2016/|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third Parties]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Pennsylvania, 2016|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|''46%'' ''138''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|''53%'' ''159''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|''1%'' ''2''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Pennsylvania, 2012|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|''55%'' ''180''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|''44%'' ''144''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|''1%'' ''3''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Pittsburgh Metro Area}}\n{{Allegheny County, Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1913]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1913 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosslyn_Farms,_Pennsylvania"}
{"title_page": "Chicago Bee Building", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Chicago Bee Building\n| image = 20070601 Chicago Bee Building (3).JPG\n| designated_other1_name = Chicago Landmark\n| designated_other1_date = September 9, 1998\n| designated_other1_abbr = CL\n| designated_other1_link = Chicago Landmark\n| designated_other1_color = #aaccff\n| locmapin = United States Chicago#Illinois#USA\n| location = 3647-55 S. [[State Street (Chicago)|State St.]]<br />[[Chicago, IL]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|49|40.94|N|87|37|34.26|W|display=inline,title}}\n| built = 1929\n| architect = Smith, Z. Erol\n| architecture = [[Art Deco]]\n| added = April 30, 1986\n| governing_body = Private\n| mpsub = Black Metropolis TR\n| refnum = 86001090 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Chicago Bee Building''' is a historic building on Chicago's [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]].  It originally housed the ''[[Chicago Bee]]'', a newspaper serving the African Americans of Chicago. The building now houses the Chicago Bee Branch of the [[Chicago Public Library]].<ref name=\"CL\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chipublib.org/002branches/cbee/cbee.html|accessdate=May 12, 2007|date=October 2004|title=Chicago Bee Branch|publisher=Chicago Public Library}}</ref> The building was named a [[Chicago Landmark]] on September 9, 1998. It is located in the [[Black Metropolis-Bronzeville District]] in the [[Douglas, Chicago|Douglas]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]], [[Illinois]].\n\nThe ''Chicago Bee'' was founded by the African American entrepreneur [[Anthony Overton]] in 1926. This building was Overton's affirmation of his confidence in the viability of the State Street Commercial district. This three-story building was one of the most picturesque in the district, and the one designed in the Art Deco style of the 1920s. All of Overton's enterprises shared this building until the early 1940s when the newspaper went out of business. The cosmetics firm continued to occupy the building until the early 1980s. The City of Chicago purchased the building and it is now a Chicago Public Library. It originally had upper-floor apartments. It also housed the offices of the Douglass National Bank and the [[Overton Hygienic Company]], during the 1930s. The Overton Hygienic Company was nationally known as a cosmetics firm.\n\nOverton Hygienic went out of business in the early 1980s. In the mid-1990s, the building was reused as a branch of the Chicago Public Library. It is one of nine structures in the Black Metropolis-Bronzeville Historic District.<ref name=CL>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/C/ChicagoBee.html|title=Chicago Bee Building|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|year=2003|accessdate=May 12, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070428044149/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/C/ChicagoBee.html|archivedate=April 28, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on April 30, 1986.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:20070601 Chicago Bee Building (2).JPG\nImage:20070601 Chicago Bee Building.JPG\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101031054757/http://www.tourblackchicago.com/blog/flavor/chicago-bee-building/ Chicago Bee Building], Tour Black Chicago\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Chicago Bee Building}}\n* {{NRHP url|id=64000173|title=National Register of Historic Places Multiple Property Submission: Black Metropolis Thematic Nomination}}\n\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Office buildings in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Chicago Landmarks]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings completed in 1929]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in Illinois]]\n[[Category:African-American history in Chicago]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Chicago Bee Building\n| image = 20070601 Chicago Bee Building (3).JPG\n| designated_other1_name = Chicago Landmark\n| designated_other1_date = September 9, 1998\n| designated_other1_abbr = CL\n| designated_other1_link = Chicago Landmark\n| designated_other1_color = #aaccff\n| locmapin = United States Chicago#Illinois#USA\n| location = 3647-55 S. [[State Street (Chicago)|State St.]]<br />[[Chicago, IL]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|49|40.94|N|87|37|34.26|W|display=inline,title}}\n| built = 1929\n| architect = Smith, Z. Erol\n| architecture = [[Art Deco]]\n| added = April 30, 1986\n| governing_body = Private\n| mpsub = Black Metropolis TR\n| refnum = 86001090 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Chicago Bee Building''' is a historic building on Chicago's [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]].  It originally housed the ''[[Chicago Bee]]'', a newspaper serving the African Americans of Chicago. The building now houses the Chicago Bee Branch of the [[Chicago Public Library]].<ref name=\"CL\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chipublib.org/002branches/cbee/cbee.html|accessdate=May 12, 2007|date=October 2004|title=Chicago Bee Branch|publisher=Chicago Public Library}}</ref> The building was named a [[Chicago Landmark]] on September 9, 1998. It is located in the [[Black Metropolis-Bronzeville District]] in the [[Douglas, Chicago|Douglas]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]], [[Illinois]].\n\nThe ''Chicago Bee'' was founded by the African American entrepreneur [[Anthony Overton]] in 1926. This building was Overton's affirmation of his confidence in the viability of the State Street Commercial district. This three-story building was one of the most picturesque in the district, and the one designed in the Art Deco style of the 1920s. All of Overton's enterprises shared this building until the early 1940s when the newspaper went out of business. The cosmetics firm continued to occupy the building until the early 1980s. The City of Chicago purchased the building and it is now a Chicago Public Library. It originally had upper-floor apartments. It also housed the offices of the Douglass National Bank and the [[Overton Hygienic Company]], during the 1930s. The Overton Hygienic Company was nationally known as a cosmetics firm.\n\nOverton Hygienic went out of business in the early 1980s. In the mid-1990s, the building was reused as a branch of the Chicago Public Library. It is one of nine structures in the Black Metropolis-Bronzeville Historic District.<ref name=CL>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/C/ChicagoBee.html|title=Chicago Bee Building|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|year=2003|accessdate=May 12, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070428044149/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/C/ChicagoBee.html|archivedate=April 28, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on April 30, 1986.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:20070601 Chicago Bee Building (2).JPG\nImage:20070601 Chicago Bee Building.JPG\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101031054757/http://www.tourblackchicago.com/blog/flavor/chicago-bee-building/ Chicago Bee Building], Tour Black Chicago\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Chicago Bee Building}}\n* {{NRHP url|id=64000173|title=National Register of Historic Places Multiple Property Submission: Black Metropolis Thematic Nomination}}\n\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Office buildings in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings completed in 1929]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in Illinois]]\n[[Category:African-American history in Chicago]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Bee_Building"}
{"title_page": "Roseville, Pennsylvania", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Rouseville, Pennsylvania}}\n{{For|the community in Jefferson County|Roseville, Jefferson County, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name = Roseville, Pennsylvania\n| native_name = \n| other_name = \n| settlement_type = [[Borough (Pennsylvania)|Borough]]\n<!-- images and maps ----------->\n| image_skyline = PA 549 in Roseville.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| image_caption = [[Pennsylvania Route 549|PA&nbsp;549 southbound]] through Roseville.\n| image_flag = \n| image_seal = \n| image_shield = \n| nickname = \n| motto = \n| image_map = File:Tioga County Pennsylvania Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Roseville Highlighted.svg\n| mapsize = 250x200px\n| map_caption = Location of Roseville in Tioga County, Pennsylvania.\n| pushpin_map = Pennsylvania#USA\n| pushpin_label = Roseville\n| pushpin_label_position = left <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_mapsize = <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within the U.S. state of Pennsylvania\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|51|50|N|76|57|18|W|region:US-PA|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name = United States\n| subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Pennsylvania|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Tioga County, Pennsylvania|Tioga]]\n| established_title = Settled\n| established_date = 1806\n| established_title2 = Incorporated (borough)\n| established_date2 = 1876\n| government_type = \n| government_footnotes = \n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n<!-- Area --------------------->\n| unit_pref = Imperial\n| area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_42.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Mar 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2 = 1.23\n| area_total_sq_mi = 0.47\n| area_land_km2 = 1.23\n| area_water_km2 = 0.00\n| area_water_percent = \n| elevation_footnotes = \n| elevation_m = \n| elevation_ft = 1342\n<!-- Population ----------------------->\n| population_footnotes = \n| population_total = 189\n| population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_density_km2 = 151.87\n| population_density_sq_mi = 393.68\n| population_note = \n<!-- General information --------------->\n| timezone = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n| utc_offset = \n| timezone_DST = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST = \n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type = Zip\n| postal_code = \n| area_code = [[Area code 570|570]]\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2017\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2017\"/>\n|population_est = 187\n|blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info = 42-66232\n|area_land_sq_mi = 0.47\n|area_water_sq_mi = 0.00\n}}\n'''Roseville''' is a [[Borough (Pennsylvania)|borough]] in [[Tioga County, Pennsylvania|Tioga County]], [[Pennsylvania]], in the United States. The population was 189 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"censusviewer.com\">http://censusviewer.com/city/PA/Roseville%20%28Rutland%29</ref>\n\n==History==\nRoseville was first settled by its namesake, Dr. William Rose in 1806. Dr. Rose migrated to Tioga County from [[Rutland (town), Vermont]]. He served as a frontier doctor for the citizens of eastern Tioga and western [[Bradford County, Pennsylvania|Bradford Counties]]. Rose built a [[distillery]] at Roseville in 1822, soon after his son, William Rose Jr., opened a [[tavern]]. The tavern quickly became the center of commerce in Roseville. The tavern was replaced by a [[hotel]] built to serve the needs to travelers between [[Mansfield, Pennsylvania|Mansfield]] and [[Elmira, New York|Elmira]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\"Rosevillehistory\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rootsweb.com/~srgp/articles/roseville150.htm | title = Roseville's 150 years | accessdate = 2008-01-15 | author = The Elmira Telegram | publisher = Joyce M. Tice (Rootsweb)| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071118024652/http://www.rootsweb.com/~srgp/articles/roseville150.htm| archivedate = November 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\nRoseville was home to several businesses that served the needs of the people of Tioga County during the late 1800s and early 1900s. A [[gristmill]] was opened as was a cheese factory and a paint plant, but the principal form of business remained in the taverns along the highway. A devastating fire in 1888 destroyed 23 buildings in Roseville, thus ending the tavern era.<ref name=\"Rosevillehistory\"/>\n\nRoseville formerly had a [[post office]] and a [[Public school (government funded)|public school]]. The post office, Rutland Post Office, was closed in 1957. The public school was closed in 1966 when Roseville's school system became part of the Mansfield school system, which later was consolidated into the [[Southern Tioga School District]].<ref name=\"Rosevillehistory\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nRoseville is located at {{Coord|41|51|51|N|76|57|34|W|type:city}} (41.864305, -76.959348).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the borough has a total area of {{convert|0.5|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.\n\nRoseville is surrounded by [[Rutland Township, Tioga County, Pennsylvania|Rutland Township]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 185\n|1890= 211\n|1900= 215\n|1920= 119\n|1930= 99\n|1940= 133\n|1950= 126\n|1960= 162\n|1970= 178\n|1980= 211\n|1990= 230\n|2000= 207\n|2010= 189\n|estyear=2017\n|estimate=187\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2017\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2017.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|footnote=Sources:<ref name=\"USDecennialCensus\">{{cite web|title=Census of Population and Housing|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref><ref name=CensusPopEst>{{cite web|title=Incorporated Places and Minor Civil Divisions Datasets: Subcounty Resident Population Estimates: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2012|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|work=Population Estimates|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611010502/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|archivedate=11 June 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2010, there were 189 people,<ref name=\"censusviewer.com\"/> 75 households, and 57 families residing in the borough. The [[population density]] was 390.0 people per square mile (150.8/km\u00b2). There were 84 housing units at an average density of 158.3 per square mile (61.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the borough was 97.58% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.48% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.97% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], and 0.97% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.48% of the population.\n\nThere were 75 households out of which 32.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.7% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 22.7% were non-families. 16.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 4.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.76 and the average family size was 3.02.\n\nIn the borough the population was spread out with 28.0% under the age of 18, 9.7% from 18 to 24, 23.2% from 25 to 44, 30.0% from 45 to 64, and 9.2% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 34 years. For every 100 females there were 99.0 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the borough was $27,188, and the median income for a family was $24,821. Males had a median income of $31,500 versus $21,667 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the borough was $11,683. About 10.5% of families and 14.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 28.8% of those under the age of eighteen and none of those sixty five or over.\n\n==Churches==\nThere are two [[church (building)|churches]] located in Roseville: Roseville [[Methodist]] Church and the [[Independent Baptist]] Church.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Tioga County, Pennsylvania}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1806]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in Tioga County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Rouseville, Pennsylvania}}\n{{For|the community in Jefferson County|Roseville, Jefferson County, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name = Roseville, Pennsylvania\n| native_name = \n| other_name = \n| settlement_type = [[Borough (Pennsylvania)|Borough]]\n<!-- images and maps ----------->\n| image_skyline = PA 549 in Roseville.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| image_caption = [[Pennsylvania Route 549|PA&nbsp;549 southbound]] through Roseville.\n| image_flag = \n| image_seal = \n| image_shield = \n| nickname = \n| motto = \n| image_map = File:Tioga County Pennsylvania Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Roseville Highlighted.svg\n| mapsize = 250x200px\n| map_caption = Location of Roseville in Tioga County, Pennsylvania.\n| pushpin_map = Pennsylvania#USA\n| pushpin_label = Roseville\n| pushpin_label_position = left <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_mapsize = <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within the U.S. state of Pennsylvania\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|51|50|N|76|57|18|W|region:US-PA|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name = United States\n| subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Pennsylvania|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Tioga County, Pennsylvania|Tioga]]\n| established_title = Settled\n| established_date = 1806\n| established_title2 = Incorporated (borough)\n| established_date2 = 1876\n| government_type = \n| government_footnotes = \n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n<!-- Area --------------------->\n| unit_pref = Imperial\n| area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_42.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Mar 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2 = 1.23\n| area_total_sq_mi = 0.47\n| area_land_km2 = 1.23\n| area_water_km2 = 0.00\n| area_water_percent = \n| elevation_footnotes = \n| elevation_m = \n| elevation_ft = 1342\n<!-- Population ----------------------->\n| population_footnotes = \n| population_total = 189\n| population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_density_km2 = 151.87\n| population_density_sq_mi = 393.68\n| population_note = \n<!-- General information --------------->\n| timezone = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n| utc_offset = \n| timezone_DST = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST = \n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type = Zip\n| postal_code = \n| area_code = [[Area code 570|570]]\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2017\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2017\"/>\n|population_est = 187\n|blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info = 42-66232\n|area_land_sq_mi = 0.47\n|area_water_sq_mi = 0.00\n}}\n'''Roseville''' is a [[Borough (Pennsylvania)|borough]] in [[Tioga County, Pennsylvania|Tioga County]], [[Pennsylvania]], in the United States. The population was 189 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"censusviewer.com\">http://censusviewer.com/city/PA/Roseville%20%28Rutland%29</ref>\n\n==History==\nRoseville was first settled by its namesake, Dr. William Rose in 1806. Dr. Rose migrated to Tioga County from [[Rutland (town), Vermont]]. He served as a frontier doctor for the citizens of eastern Tioga and western [[Bradford County, Pennsylvania|Bradford Counties]]. Rose built a [[distillery]] at Roseville in 1822, soon after his son, William Rose Jr., opened a [[tavern]]. The tavern quickly became the center of commerce in Roseville. The tavern was replaced by a [[hotel]] built to serve the needs to travelers between [[Mansfield, Pennsylvania|Mansfield]] and [[Elmira, New York|Elmira]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\"Rosevillehistory\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rootsweb.com/~srgp/articles/roseville150.htm | title = Roseville's 150 years | accessdate = 2008-01-15 | author = The Elmira Telegram | publisher = Joyce M. Tice (Rootsweb)| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071118024652/http://www.rootsweb.com/~srgp/articles/roseville150.htm| archivedate = November 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\nRoseville was home to several businesses that served the needs of the people of Tioga County during the late 1800s and early 1900s. A [[gristmill]] was opened as was a cheese factory and a paint plant, but the principal form of business remained in the taverns along the highway. A devastating fire in 1888 destroyed 23 buildings in Roseville, thus ending the tavern era.<ref name=\"Rosevillehistory\"/>\n\nRoseville formerly had a [[post office]] and a [[Public school (government funded)|public school]]. The post office, Rutland Post Office, was closed in 1957. The public school was closed in 1966 when Roseville's school system became part of the Mansfield school system, which later was consolidated into the [[Southern Tioga School District]].<ref name=\"Rosevillehistory\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nRoseville is located at {{Coord|41|51|51|N|76|57|34|W|type:city}} (41.864305, -76.959348).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the borough has a total area of {{convert|0.5|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.\n\nRoseville is surrounded by [[Rutland Township, Tioga County, Pennsylvania|Rutland Township]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 185\n|1890= 211\n|1900= 215\n|1920= 119\n|1930= 99\n|1940= 133\n|1950= 126\n|1960= 162\n|1970= 178\n|1980= 211\n|1990= 230\n|2000= 207\n|2010= 189\n|estyear=2017\n|estimate=187\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2017\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2017.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|footnote=Sources:<ref name=\"USDecennialCensus\">{{cite web|title=Census of Population and Housing|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref><ref name=CensusPopEst>{{cite web|title=Incorporated Places and Minor Civil Divisions Datasets: Subcounty Resident Population Estimates: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2012|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|work=Population Estimates|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611010502/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|archivedate=11 June 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2010, there were 189 people,<ref name=\"censusviewer.com\"/> 75 households, and 57 families residing in the borough. The [[population density]] was 390.0 people per square mile (150.8/km\u00b2). There were 84 housing units at an average density of 158.3 per square mile (61.2/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the borough was 97.58% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.48% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.97% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], and 0.97% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.48% of the population.\n\nThere were 75 households out of which 32.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.7% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 22.7% were non-families. 16.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 4.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.76 and the average family size was 3.02.\n\nIn the borough the population was spread out with 28.0% under the age of 18, 9.7% from 18 to 24, 23.2% from 25 to 44, 30.0% from 45 to 64, and 9.2% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 34 years. For every 100 females there were 99.0 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the borough was $27,188, and the median income for a family was $24,821. Males had a median income of $31,500 versus $21,667 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the borough was $11,683. About 10.5% of families and 14.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 28.8% of those under the age of eighteen and none of those sixty five or over.\n\n==Churches==\nThere are two [[church (building)|churches]] located in Roseville: Roseville [[Methodist]] Church and the [[Independent Baptist]] Church.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Tioga County, Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1806]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in Tioga County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roseville,_Pennsylvania"}
{"title_page": "Koko Pimentel", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Filipino politician}}\n{{Philippine name|de la Llana|Pimentel}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| name             = Koko Pimentel\n| image            = SKP2.jpg\n| image_size       = 220px\n| caption          = Senator Koko Pimentel\n| office1          = [[Senate of the Philippines|Senator of the Philippines]]\n| term_start1      = August 11, 2011\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin| Senate  committee chairmanships}}\n| office2          = Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Senate Committee on <br> Foreign Relations]]\n| term_start2      = July 23, 2019\n| term_end2        = \n| predecessor2     = [[Loren Legarda]]\n| successor2       =\n| office3          = Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Senate Committee on <br> Trade, Commerce and Entrepreneurship]]\n| term_start3      = May 25, 2018\n| term_end3        = \n| predecessor3     = [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]]\n| successor3       = \n| office4          = Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Senate Committee on <br> Electoral Reforms and People's Participation]]\n| term_start4      = July 24, 2018\n| term_end4        = July 22, 2019\n| predecessor4     = [[Leila de Lima]]\n| successor4       = [[Imee Marcos]]\n|term_start5       = July 22, 2013\n|term_end5         = July 25, 2016\n|predecessor5      = ''office created''\n|successor5        = Leila de Lima\n| office6          = Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Senate Committee on <br> Justice and Human Rights]]\n| term_start6      = July 22, 2013\n| term_end6        = July 25, 2016\n| predecessor6     = [[Francis Escudero]]\n| successor6       = [[Leila de Lima]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n| office7           = [[President of the Senate of the Philippines#List of Senate Presidents|28th]] [[President of the Senate of the Philippines]]\n| president7        = \n| term_start7       = July 25, 2016\n| term_end7         = May 21, 2018\n| succeeding       = \n| predecessor8      = [[Franklin Drilon]]\n| successor8        = [[Tito Sotto]]\n| office9          = [[National Youth Commission (Philippines)|National Youth Commission]] Commissioner for [[Mindanao]]\n| term_start9      = 1996\n| term_end9        = 1998\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1964|01|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cagayan de Oro]], [[Misamis Oriental]], Philippines\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| birthname        = Aquilino Martin de la Llana Pimentel III\n| nationality      = [[Filipinos|Filipino]]\n| party            = [[PDP\u2013Laban]] (1990\u2013present)\n| otherparty       = \n| spouse           = {{marriage|Jewel May Lobaton|2000|2012|reason=separated}} <br> {{marriage|[[Kathryna Yu-Pimentel|Kathryna Yu]]|2018}}\n| parents          = [[Aquilino Pimentel Jr.]] <br> Lourdes de la Llana-Pimentel\n| children         = 2\n| alma_mater       = [[Ateneo de Manila University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]])}} <br> [[University of the Philippines Diliman]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])}}\n| occupation       = Politician\n| profession       = Lawyer and Lecturer\n| net_worth        = [[Philippine peso|\u20b1]]18 million (2017)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ager|first1=Maila|title=Cynthia Villar remains richest senator|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/991623/cynthia-villar-remains-richest-senator-villar-senate-saln-senators|accessdate=May 29, 2018|newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=May 17, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517062735/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/991623/cynthia-villar-remains-richest-senator-villar-senate-saln-senators|archivedate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n'''Aquilino Martin de la Llana Pimentel III''' (born January 20, 1964), commonly known as '''Koko Pimentel''',  is a Filipino politician and lawyer currently serving as a [[Senate of the Philippines|Senator of the Philippines]]. He was the 28th [[President of the Senate of the Philippines|Senate President of the Philippines]] from 2016 to 2018.<ref>Lardizabal. C. (July 26, 2016). [http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2016/07/25/koko-pimentel-senate-president-17th-congress.html Koko Pimentel elected as Senate President of 17th Congress]. ''CNN Philippines''.</ref><ref>[http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2016/07/25/1606275/pimentel-elected-senate-president Pimentel elected as Senate president]. (July 25, 2016). ''The Philippine Star''.</ref> He is also the current party president of Partido Demokratiko Pilipino\u2013Lakas ng Bayan ([[PDP\u2013Laban]]). As the eldest son and third child of the former Senate President [[Aquilino Pimentel Jr.]], he is  the first child of a previous Senate president to hold the office.<ref>Quismundo, T. (July 26, 2016). [http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/799462/the-son-also-rises-koko-pimentel-makes-history/2 The son also rises: Koko Pimentel makes history]. ''Philippine Daily Inquirer''</ref> He was sworn in on August 12, 2011 and was proclaimed as the 12th winning senator in the [[2007 Philippine Senate election|2007 election]].<ref>[http://www.sunstar.com.ph/manila/local-news/2011/08/11/pimentel-proclaimed-senator-172340 Pimentel proclaimed as senator]. Sunstar.com.ph (August 4, 2011). Retrieved on 2011-08-12.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAquilino Martin de la Llana Pimentel III was born on January 20, 1964 in [[Cagayan de Oro]], Philippines.<ref name=\"koko\" /><ref name=\"nene\" /> His parents are [[Aquilino Pimentel, Jr.]] and Lourdes de la Llana-Pimentel. His father was a lawyer and [[Dean (education)|dean]] of [[Law school|law]] at [[Xavier University \u2013 Ateneo de Cagayan|Xavier University]] at the time of his birth. The elder Pimentel eventually became a senator.<ref name=\"nene\">[http://www.nenepimentel.org/?page=bio Bio Data]. ''The Official Website of Senator Aquilino \"Nene\" Q. Pimentel, Jr.''</ref>\n\nPimentel earned his Bachelor of Science degree in Mathematics from [[Ateneo de Manila University]] and his [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[University of the Philippines College of Law]].<ref name=\"koko\" /><ref name=\"nene\" /> He topped the 1990 [[Philippine Bar Examination]]s with a score of 89.85 percent.<ref>[http://www.chanrobles.com/phsupremecourt/1989-1992.php Bar Topnotchers 1989-1992]. ''ChanRobles\u2122 Virtual Law Library''.</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n[[File:Koko Pimentel.jpg|alt=|thumb]]\nPimentel began working as a lawyer in 1990, and was commissioner (representing [[Mindanao]]) on the [[National Youth Commission (Philippines)|National Youth Commission]] from 1995 to 1998. He was a professor for the [[University of the East College of Law]] from 2007 to 2010 and also for the [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]]-[[Juris Doctor|JD]] Program of the [[Ramon V. del Rosario College of Business]] and [[Far Eastern University Institute of Law]] from 2006 until his election to the senate in August 2011.<ref name=koko>[http://kokopimentel.org/about/ About Koko].</ref> He was conferred Doctor of Humanities ''honoris causa'' by the [[Polytechnic University of the Philippines]] on May 18, 2012.<ref>[http://kokopimentel.org/speeches/commencement-address-of-senator-koko-pimentel-for-the-2012-graduates-of-the-polytechnic-university-of-the-philippines-published-may-21-2012/ Commencement Address of Senator Koko Pimentel for Polytechnic University of the Philippines May 18, 2012]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===2001 election===\n\nPimentel ran for Cagayan de Oro City mayor in the [[2001 Philippine general election|2001 elections]] but lost to [[Vicente Emano]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=MACARAIG|first1=AYEE|title=Aquilino Martin 'Koko' Pimentel III: \u2018It\u2019s complicated\u2019 (September 30, 2012)|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections-2013/13342-aquilino-martin-koko-pimentel-iii-\u00e2%80%98it\u00e2%80%99s-complicated\u00e2%80%99|website=Rappler|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2007 election===\nRunning in only his second race in the [[2007 Philippine Senate election|May 14, 2007 senatorial elections]], Pimentel was narrowly defeated by [[Bukidnon]] Congressman [[Miguel Zubiri]] for the 12th and last slot in the Philippine Senate. The narrow margin of 18,372 votes was  controversial, particularly the votes from the southern Philippine province of [[Maguindanao]], where Pimentel had lost heavily to Zubiri.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=76622 Zubiri proclaimed 12th Senator] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070716152524/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=76622 |date=July 16, 2007 }}. Inquirer.net. Retrieved on August 12, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Electoral protest===\n{{main|Pimentel v. Zubiri}}\n\nIn Philippine senatorial elections, the twelve candidates with the highest number of votes nationwide are elected. In the [[2007 Philippine Senate election|2007 elections]], Pimentel ([[Genuine Opposition]]) and [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]] ([[TEAM Unity (Philippines)|TEAM Unity]]) contested the 12th seat.<ref name=\"result\" /><ref name=\"TRO\" />\n\nIn the final tally for the 2007 senatorial elections by the [[Commission on Elections (Philippines)|Commission on Elections]] (COMELEC), Zubiri narrowly defeated Pimentel for the 12th and last seat in the Senate. Zubiri had a total of 11,005,866 votes against Pimentel's 10,984,347 votes.<ref name=\"result\">{{cite news|last1=Pacheco|first1=Marieton|title=Zubiri: SC ruling on Pimentel bid seals case|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/03/14/08/zubiri-sc-ruling-pimentel-bid-seals-case|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=ABS-CBN News|date=March 14, 2008}}</ref> On July 14, 2007, Zubiri was proclaimed as the 12th winning senator.<ref name=\"TRO\">{{cite news|last1=Legaspi|first1=Amita|title=Without TRO, Zubiri proclaimed 12th senator on Saturday|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/50713/news/nation/without-tro-zubiri-proclaimed-12th-senator-on-saturday|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=GMA News|date=July 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\nClaiming fraudulent votes in 22 municipalities of [[Maguindanao]], 7 in [[Lanao del Norte]], 3 in [[Shariff Kabunsuan]], 2 in [[Basilan]], 2 in [[Sultan Kudarat]], 4 in [[Lanao del Sur]], and 4 in [[Sulu]], Pimentel petitioned the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] to issue a [[restraining order]] against the proclamation of Zubiri.  With the vote tied at 7\u20137, the Supreme Court dismissed Pimentel's petition. But then-[[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines|Chief Justice]] [[Reynato Puno]] was among the seven justices who favored Pimentel's petition.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=76486 SC paves way for Zubiri proclamation]. Inquirer.net. Retrieved on August 12, 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mendez|first1=Christina|title=Pimentel inhibits self from son's election protest|url=http://www.philstar.com:8080/headlines/11193/pimentel-inhibits-self-son%E2%80%99s-election-protest|accessdate=March 13, 2017|newspaper=The Philippine Star|date=August 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn July 14, 2007, Pimentel filed an electoral protest to the Senate Electoral Tribunal (SET). After finding grounds for a [[recount]], the SET proceeded with the protest.<ref>Linda Jumilla [http://rp1.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/06/19/08/tribunal-finds-basis-proceed-koko-2007-elections-protest Tribunal finds basis to proceed with Koko 2007 elections protest]. abs-cbnnews. June 19, 2008</ref>\n\nOn July 2011, former [[Maguindanao]] election supervisor Lintang Bedol and suspended [[Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]] governor [[Zaldy Ampatuan]] revealed that there was massive election fraud during the 2007 election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jumilla|first1=Lynda|title=Hope comes alive for Koko Pimentel|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/07/13/11/hope-comes-alive-koko-pimentel|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=''ABS-CBN News''|date=July 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2011, the Senate Electoral Tribunal released the final tally: Pimentel got 10,898,786 votes while Zubiri got 10,640,620.<ref name=\"proclaimed\">{{cite news|last1=Calonzo|first1=Andreo|title=Pimentel proclaimed 12th winning senator in '07 polls|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/229132/news/nation/pimentel-proclaimed-12th-winning-senator-in-07-polls|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=GMA News|date=August 11, 2011}}</ref> Prior to this, on August 3, 2011, Zubiri resigned from the Senate; however, he reiterated that he was not involved in the 2007 electoral fraud.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ager|first1=Maila|title=Zubiri resigns amid poll fraud scandal|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/35661/zubiri-resigns-amid-poll-fraud-scandal|accessdate=March 13, 2017|newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2011, Pimentel was proclaimed by the Senate Electoral Tribunal as the rightful winner of the 12th senate seat.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://ph.news.yahoo.com/photos/koko-pimentel-officially-proclaimed-senator-1313054651-slideshow/|title=Koko Pimentel officially proclaimed senator|publisher=Yahoo! Philippines News|date=August 11, 2011|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> In August 12, Pimentel took his oath of office before his supporters in [[Mati, Davao Oriental]], where he received a high number of votes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merue\u00f1as|first1=Mark|title=Koko Pimentel takes oath as senator|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/229222/news/nation/koko-pimentel-takes-oath-as-senator|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=GMA News|date=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2013 election===\n[[File:SONA 2016 1.png|thumb|Pimentel (top left) during President [[Rodrigo Duterte]]'s [[2016 State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|2016 State of the Nation Address]].]]\nPimentel was included in the [[United Nationalist Alliance]] (UNA) coalition's shortlist of senatorial candidates for the [[2013 Philippine Senate election|2013 election]]. However, citing UNA's senatorial slate now having more than twelve members and the inclusion of his longtime political rival, [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]], Pimentel officially declined his spot in the UNA coalition on June 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pedrasa|first1=Ira|title=It's final: Koko won't run under UNA|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/06/28/12/its-final-koko-wont-run-under-una|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=ABS-CBN News|date=June 28, 2012}}</ref> Instead, Pimentel ran under the [[Team PNoy]] coalition, composed mostly of supporters of then-President [[Benigno Aquino III]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Drilon's 12-0 agenda is for his own dreams - UNA|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/02/24/13/drilons-12-0-agenda-his-own-dreams-una|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=''ABS-CBN News''|date=February 24, 2013}}</ref> Pimentel was elected to the  Senate of the Philippines, placing eighth with 14,725,114 votes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bacani|first1=Louis|title=Comelec releases final, official vote tally for Senate polls|url=http://www.philstar.com/election-2013/2013/06/06/950868/comelec-releases-final-official-vote-tally-senate-polls|accessdate=March 13, 2017|newspaper=The Philippine Star|date=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Senate President (2016\u20132018)===\nOn July 25, 2016, the opening day of the [[17th Congress of the Philippines]], Pimentel was elected as Senate President with 20 out of 23 senators voting in his favor.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ager|first1=Maila|title=Koko Pimentel takes Senate presidency by 20-3 vote|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/798856/koko-pimentel-takes-senate-presidency-with-20-3-vote|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref> He, along with his father [[Aquilino Pimentel Jr.]], is the only father-and-son tandem being elected as Senate President in Philippine History (the elder Pimentel served as Senate President from November 13, 2000 to July 23, 2001).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Elemia|first1=Camille|title=1st in PH history: Father, son elected Senate President (July 28, 2016)|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/141202-koko-nene-pimentel-senate-president|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref> Pimentel resigned on May 21, 2018, in order to focus on his reelection bid in the [[2019 Philippine Senate election|2019]] and is succeeded by Majority Leader [[Tito Sotto]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn May 2013, Pimentel met chef [[Kathryna Yu-Pimentel|Kathryna Yu]], and they married in October 2018. Yu currently heads [[PDP Cares]], the humanitarian arm of PDP-Laban.<ref>Elemia, C. (December 20, 2017). [http://www.rappler.com/nation/192579-koko-pimentel-partner-kathryna-yu-2017-yearend Meet Pimentel's 'life partner' leading PDP-Laban's humanitarian arm]. ''Rappler''.</ref><ref>Elemia, C. (October 18, 2018). [https://www.rappler.com/nation/214642-duterte-as-ninong-koko-pimentel-kathryna-yu-wedding Ninong Duterte in Koko Pimentel, Kathryna Yu wedding]. ''Rappler''.</ref><ref name=\"RG_Cruz\">RG Cruz (October 18, 2018). [https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/18/18/koko-pimentel-weds-chef-kathryna-yu Koko Pimentel weds chef Kathryna Yu]. ''ABS-CBN News''.</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070310163912/http://www.inquirer.net/specialfeatures/eleksyon2007/candidates.php?name=Pimentel%2C-Aquilino-III-%28Koko%29 Aquilino Koko Pimentel's Biodata]\n*[http://kokopimentel.org/ Senator Koko Pimentel]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ph-upr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Francis Escudero]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate <br>Justice and Human Rights Committee]]|years=2013\u20132016}}\n{{S-aft|rows=2|after=[[Leila de Lima]]}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate Electoral Reforms and <br>People's Participation Committee]]|years=2013\u20132016}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leila de Lima]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate Electoral Reforms and <br>People's Participation Committee]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Imee Marcos]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Juan Miguel Zubiri]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate <br>Trade, Commerce and <br>Entrepreneurship Committee]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Loren Legarda]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate <br>Foreign Relations Committee]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Franklin Drilon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Senate of the Philippines]]|years=2016\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tito Sotto]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jejomar Binay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of [[PDP\u2013Laban]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Philippine Senate Presidents}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Senatorial history of Aquilino \"Koko\" Pimentel III\n|list=\n{{15th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{16th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{17th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{18th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pimentel, Koko}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ilocano people]]\n[[Category:Filipino lawyers]]\n[[Category:People from Cagayan de Oro]]\n[[Category:PDP\u2013Laban politicians]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 18th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 17th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 16th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 15th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Ateneo de Manila University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines Diliman alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Senate of the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Filipino politician}}\n{{Philippine name|de la Llana|Pimentel}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| name             = Koko Pimentel\n| image            = SKP2.jpg\n| image_size       = 220px\n| caption          = Senator Koko Pimentel\n| office1          = [[Senate of the Philippines|Senator of the Philippines]]\n| term_start1      = August 11, 2011\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin| Senate  committee chairmanships}}\n| office2          = Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Senate Committee on <br> Foreign Relations]]\n| term_start2      = July 23, 2019\n| term_end2        = \n| predecessor2     = [[Loren Legarda]]\n| successor2       =\n| office3          = Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Senate Committee on <br> Trade, Commerce and Entrepreneurship]]\n| term_start3      = May 25, 2018\n| term_end3        = \n| predecessor3     = [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]]\n| successor3       = \n| office4          = Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Senate Committee on <br> Electoral Reforms and People's Participation]]\n| term_start4      = July 24, 2018\n| term_end4        = July 22, 2019\n| predecessor4     = [[Leila de Lima]]\n| successor4       = [[Imee Marcos]]\n|term_start5       = July 22, 2013\n|term_end5         = July 25, 2016\n|predecessor5      = ''office created''\n|successor5        = Leila de Lima\n| office6          = Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Senate Committee on <br> Justice and Human Rights]]\n| term_start6      = July 22, 2013\n| term_end6        = July 25, 2016\n| predecessor6     = [[Francis Escudero]]\n| successor6       = [[Leila de Lima]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n| office7           = [[President of the Senate of the Philippines#List of Senate Presidents|28th]] [[President of the Senate of the Philippines]]\n| president7        = \n| term_start7       = July 25, 2016\n| term_end7         = May 21, 2018\n| succeeding       = \n| predecessor8      = [[Franklin Drilon]]\n| successor8        = [[Tito Sotto]]\n| office9          = [[National Youth Commission (Philippines)|National Youth Commission]] Commissioner for [[Mindanao]]\n| term_start9      = 1996\n| term_end9        = 1998\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1964|01|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cagayan de Oro]], [[Misamis Oriental]], Philippines\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| birthname        = Aquilino Martin de la Llana Pimentel III\n| nationality      = [[Filipinos|Filipino]]\n| party            = [[PDP\u2013Laban]] (1990\u2013present)\n| otherparty       = \n| spouse           = {{marriage|Jewel May Lobaton|2000|2012|reason=separated}} <br> {{marriage|[[Kathryna Yu-Pimentel|Kathryna Yu]]|2018}}\n| parents          = [[Aquilino Pimentel Jr.]] <br> Lourdes de la Llana-Pimentel\n| children         = 2\n| alma_mater       = [[Ateneo de Manila University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]])}} <br> [[University of the Philippines Diliman]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])}}\n| occupation       = Politician\n| profession       = Lawyer and Lecturer\n| net_worth        = [[Philippine peso|\u20b1]]18 million (2017)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ager|first1=Maila|title=Cynthia Villar remains richest senator|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/991623/cynthia-villar-remains-richest-senator-villar-senate-saln-senators|accessdate=May 29, 2018|newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=May 17, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517062735/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/991623/cynthia-villar-remains-richest-senator-villar-senate-saln-senators|archivedate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n'''Aquilino Martin de la Llana Pimentel III''' (born January 20, 1964), commonly known as '''Koko Pimentel''',  is a Filipino politician and lawyer currently serving as a [[Senate of the Philippines|Senator of the Philippines]]. He was the 28th [[President of the Senate of the Philippines|Senate President of the Philippines]] from 2016 to 2018.<ref>Lardizabal. C. (July 26, 2016). [http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2016/07/25/koko-pimentel-senate-president-17th-congress.html Koko Pimentel elected as Senate President of 17th Congress]. ''CNN Philippines''.</ref><ref>[http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2016/07/25/1606275/pimentel-elected-senate-president Pimentel elected as Senate president]. (July 25, 2016). ''The Philippine Star''.</ref> He is also the current party president of Partido Demokratiko Pilipino\u2013Lakas ng Bayan ([[PDP\u2013Laban]]). As the eldest son and third child of the former Senate President [[Aquilino Pimentel Jr.]], he is  the first child of a previous Senate president to hold the office.<ref>Quismundo, T. (July 26, 2016). [http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/799462/the-son-also-rises-koko-pimentel-makes-history/2 The son also rises: Koko Pimentel makes history]. ''Philippine Daily Inquirer''</ref> He was sworn in on August 12, 2011 and was proclaimed as the 12th winning senator in the [[2007 Philippine Senate election|2007 election]].<ref>[http://www.sunstar.com.ph/manila/local-news/2011/08/11/pimentel-proclaimed-senator-172340 Pimentel proclaimed as senator]. Sunstar.com.ph (August 4, 2011). Retrieved on 2011-08-12.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAquilino Martin de la Llana Pimentel III was born on January 20, 1964 in [[Cagayan de Oro]], Philippines.<ref name=\"koko\" /><ref name=\"nene\" /> His parents are [[Aquilino Pimentel, Jr.]] and Lourdes de la Llana-Pimentel. His father was a lawyer and [[Dean (education)|dean]] of [[Law school|law]] at [[Xavier University \u2013 Ateneo de Cagayan|Xavier University]] at the time of his birth. The elder Pimentel eventually became a senator.<ref name=\"nene\">[http://www.nenepimentel.org/?page=bio Bio Data]. ''The Official Website of Senator Aquilino \"Nene\" Q. Pimentel, Jr.''</ref>\n\nPimentel earned his Bachelor of Science degree in Mathematics from [[Ateneo de Manila University]] and his [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[University of the Philippines College of Law]].<ref name=\"koko\" /><ref name=\"nene\" /> He topped the 1990 [[Philippine Bar Examination]]s with a score of 89.85 percent.<ref>[http://www.chanrobles.com/phsupremecourt/1989-1992.php Bar Topnotchers 1989-1992]. ''ChanRobles\u2122 Virtual Law Library''.</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n[[File:Koko Pimentel.jpg|alt=|thumb]]\nPimentel began working as a lawyer in 1990, and was commissioner (representing [[Mindanao]]) on the [[National Youth Commission (Philippines)|National Youth Commission]] from 1995 to 1998. He was a professor for the [[University of the East College of Law]] from 2007 to 2010 and also for the [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]]-[[Juris Doctor|JD]] Program of the [[Ramon V. del Rosario College of Business]] and [[Far Eastern University Institute of Law]] from 2006 until his election to the senate in August 2011.<ref name=koko>[http://kokopimentel.org/about/ About Koko].</ref> He was conferred Doctor of Humanities ''honoris causa'' by the [[Polytechnic University of the Philippines]] on May 18, 2012.<ref>[http://kokopimentel.org/speeches/commencement-address-of-senator-koko-pimentel-for-the-2012-graduates-of-the-polytechnic-university-of-the-philippines-published-may-21-2012/ Commencement Address of Senator Koko Pimentel for Polytechnic University of the Philippines May 18, 2012]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===2001 election===\n\nPimentel ran for Cagayan de Oro City mayor in the [[2001 Philippine general election|2001 elections]] but lost to [[Vicente Emano]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=MACARAIG|first1=AYEE|title=Aquilino Martin 'Koko' Pimentel III: \u2018It\u2019s complicated\u2019 (September 30, 2012)|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections-2013/13342-aquilino-martin-koko-pimentel-iii-\u00e2%80%98it\u00e2%80%99s-complicated\u00e2%80%99|website=Rappler|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2007 election===\nRunning in only his second race in the [[2007 Philippine Senate election|May 14, 2007 senatorial elections]], Pimentel was narrowly defeated by [[Bukidnon]] Congressman [[Miguel Zubiri]] for the 12th and last slot in the Philippine Senate. The narrow margin of 18,372 votes was  controversial, particularly the votes from the southern Philippine province of [[Maguindanao]], where Pimentel had lost heavily to Zubiri.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=76622 Zubiri proclaimed 12th Senator] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070716152524/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=76622 |date=July 16, 2007 }}. Inquirer.net. Retrieved on August 12, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Electoral protest===\n{{main|Pimentel v. Zubiri}}\n\nIn Philippine senatorial elections, the twelve candidates with the highest number of votes nationwide are elected. In the [[2007 Philippine Senate election|2007 elections]], Pimentel ([[Genuine Opposition]]) and [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]] ([[TEAM Unity (Philippines)|TEAM Unity]]) contested the 12th seat.<ref name=\"result\" /><ref name=\"TRO\" />\n\nIn the final tally for the 2007 senatorial elections by the [[Commission on Elections (Philippines)|Commission on Elections]] (COMELEC), Zubiri narrowly defeated Pimentel for the 12th and last seat in the Senate. Zubiri had a total of 11,005,866 votes against Pimentel's 10,984,347 votes.<ref name=\"result\">{{cite news|last1=Pacheco|first1=Marieton|title=Zubiri: SC ruling on Pimentel bid seals case|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/03/14/08/zubiri-sc-ruling-pimentel-bid-seals-case|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=ABS-CBN News|date=March 14, 2008}}</ref> On July 14, 2007, Zubiri was proclaimed as the 12th winning senator.<ref name=\"TRO\">{{cite news|last1=Legaspi|first1=Amita|title=Without TRO, Zubiri proclaimed 12th senator on Saturday|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/50713/news/nation/without-tro-zubiri-proclaimed-12th-senator-on-saturday|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=GMA News|date=July 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\nClaiming fraudulent votes in 22 municipalities of [[Maguindanao]], 7 in [[Lanao del Norte]], 3 in [[Shariff Kabunsuan]], 2 in [[Basilan]], 2 in [[Sultan Kudarat]], 4 in [[Lanao del Sur]], and 4 in [[Sulu]], Pimentel petitioned the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] to issue a [[restraining order]] against the proclamation of Zubiri.  With the vote tied at 7\u20137, the Supreme Court dismissed Pimentel's petition. But then-[[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines|Chief Justice]] [[Reynato Puno]] was among the seven justices who favored Pimentel's petition.<ref>[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=76486 SC paves way for Zubiri proclamation]. Inquirer.net. Retrieved on August 12, 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mendez|first1=Christina|title=Pimentel inhibits self from son's election protest|url=http://www.philstar.com:8080/headlines/11193/pimentel-inhibits-self-son%E2%80%99s-election-protest|accessdate=March 13, 2017|newspaper=The Philippine Star|date=August 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn July 14, 2007, Pimentel filed an electoral protest to the Senate Electoral Tribunal (SET). After finding grounds for a [[recount]], the SET proceeded with the protest.<ref>Linda Jumilla [http://rp1.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/06/19/08/tribunal-finds-basis-proceed-koko-2007-elections-protest Tribunal finds basis to proceed with Koko 2007 elections protest]. abs-cbnnews. June 19, 2008</ref>\n\nOn July 2011, former [[Maguindanao]] election supervisor Lintang Bedol and suspended [[Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]] governor [[Zaldy Ampatuan]] revealed that there was massive election fraud during the 2007 election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jumilla|first1=Lynda|title=Hope comes alive for Koko Pimentel|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/07/13/11/hope-comes-alive-koko-pimentel|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=''ABS-CBN News''|date=July 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2011, the Senate Electoral Tribunal released the final tally: Pimentel got 10,898,786 votes while Zubiri got 10,640,620.<ref name=\"proclaimed\">{{cite news|last1=Calonzo|first1=Andreo|title=Pimentel proclaimed 12th winning senator in '07 polls|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/229132/news/nation/pimentel-proclaimed-12th-winning-senator-in-07-polls|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=GMA News|date=August 11, 2011}}</ref> Prior to this, on August 3, 2011, Zubiri resigned from the Senate; however, he reiterated that he was not involved in the 2007 electoral fraud.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ager|first1=Maila|title=Zubiri resigns amid poll fraud scandal|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/35661/zubiri-resigns-amid-poll-fraud-scandal|accessdate=March 13, 2017|newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn August 11, 2011, Pimentel was proclaimed by the Senate Electoral Tribunal as the rightful winner of the 12th senate seat.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://ph.news.yahoo.com/photos/koko-pimentel-officially-proclaimed-senator-1313054651-slideshow/|title=Koko Pimentel officially proclaimed senator|publisher=Yahoo! Philippines News|date=August 11, 2011|accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> In August 12, Pimentel took his oath of office before his supporters in [[Mati, Davao Oriental]], where he received a high number of votes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merue\u00f1as|first1=Mark|title=Koko Pimentel takes oath as senator|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/229222/news/nation/koko-pimentel-takes-oath-as-senator|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=GMA News|date=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2013 election===\n[[File:SONA 2016 1.png|thumb|Pimentel (top left) during President [[Rodrigo Duterte]]'s [[2016 State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|2016 State of the Nation Address]].]]\nPimentel was included in the [[United Nationalist Alliance]] (UNA) coalition's shortlist of senatorial candidates for the [[2013 Philippine Senate election|2013 election]]. However, citing UNA's senatorial slate now having more than twelve members and the inclusion of his longtime political rival, [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]], Pimentel officially declined his spot in the UNA coalition on June 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pedrasa|first1=Ira|title=It's final: Koko won't run under UNA|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/06/28/12/its-final-koko-wont-run-under-una|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=ABS-CBN News|date=June 28, 2012}}</ref> Instead, Pimentel ran under the [[Team PNoy]] coalition, composed mostly of supporters of then-President [[Benigno Aquino III]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Drilon's 12-0 agenda is for his own dreams - UNA|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/02/24/13/drilons-12-0-agenda-his-own-dreams-una|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=''ABS-CBN News''|date=February 24, 2013}}</ref> Pimentel was elected to the  Senate of the Philippines, placing eighth with 14,725,114 votes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bacani|first1=Louis|title=Comelec releases final, official vote tally for Senate polls|url=http://www.philstar.com/election-2013/2013/06/06/950868/comelec-releases-final-official-vote-tally-senate-polls|accessdate=March 13, 2017|newspaper=The Philippine Star|date=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Senate President (2016\u20132018)===\nOn July 25, 2016, the opening day of the [[17th Congress of the Philippines]], Pimentel was elected as Senate President with 20 out of 23 senators voting in his favor.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ager|first1=Maila|title=Koko Pimentel takes Senate presidency by 20-3 vote|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/798856/koko-pimentel-takes-senate-presidency-with-20-3-vote|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref> He, along with his father [[Aquilino Pimentel Jr.]], is the only father-and-son tandem being elected as Senate President in Philippine History (the elder Pimentel served as Senate President from November 13, 2000 to July 23, 2001).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Elemia|first1=Camille|title=1st in PH history: Father, son elected Senate President (July 28, 2016)|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/141202-koko-nene-pimentel-senate-president|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref> Pimentel resigned on May 21, 2018, in order to focus on his reelection bid in the [[2019 Philippine Senate election|2019]] and is succeeded by Majority Leader [[Tito Sotto]].\n\n==Personal life==\nHis sister, Gwendolyn Pimentel-Gana was appointed in 2015 as a commissioner of the [[Commission on Human Rights (Philippines)|Commission on Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PNoy appoints former LP exec as new CHR chair|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/506098/news/nation/pnoy-appoints-former-lp-exec-as-new-chr-chair|accessdate=March 13, 2017|agency=''GMA News''|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2000, Pimentel married 1998 [[Miss Universe Philippines]] Jewel May Lobaton, with whom he has two sons.<ref>Macairan, E. (2013, August 14). [http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2013/08/14/1088221/kokos-wife-eyes-abuse-raps Koko\u2019s wife eyes 'abuse' raps]. ''The Philippine Star''.</ref> Lobaton is a distant cousin of fellow senator [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]], who happens to be Pimentel's political rival.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Macaraig|first1=Ayee|title=Migz on Koko wife: I have witnesses|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/23949-migz-koko-wife-witnesses|accessdate=13 March 2017|agency=Rappler|date=March 16, 2013}}</ref> Pimentel and Lobaton have been living separately since November 2011.<ref>Esguerra, C. V. & Ager, M. (2012, May 23). [http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/198489/senator-pimentel-announces-separation-from-wife-of-12-years It's official: Koko Pimentel, wife part ways]. ''Philippine Daily Inquirer''.</ref> They officially separated in May 2012.<ref name=\"RG_Cruz\" />\n\nIn May 2013, Pimentel met chef [[Kathryna Yu-Pimentel|Kathryna Yu]], and they married in October 2018 at the [[Coconut Palace]]. Supreme Court Associate Justice [[Antonio Carpio]] officiated the wedding, while President Rodrigo Duterte, Secretary [[Bong Go]], Senate President [[Tito Sotto]], Senator [[Manny Pacquiao]] and former House Speaker [[Pantaleon Alvarez]] were [[Marriage and wedding customs in the Philippines#Ceremonial sponsors, witnesses, and participants|principal sponsors]]. Yu currently heads [[PDP Cares]], the humanitarian arm of PDP-Laban.<ref>Elemia, C. (December 20, 2017). [http://www.rappler.com/nation/192579-koko-pimentel-partner-kathryna-yu-2017-yearend Meet Pimentel's 'life partner' leading PDP-Laban's humanitarian arm]. ''Rappler''.</ref><ref>Elemia, C. (October 18, 2018). [https://www.rappler.com/nation/214642-duterte-as-ninong-koko-pimentel-kathryna-yu-wedding Ninong Duterte in Koko Pimentel, Kathryna Yu wedding]. ''Rappler''.</ref><ref name=RG_Cruz>RG Cruz (October 18, 2018). [https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/18/18/koko-pimentel-weds-chef-kathryna-yu Koko Pimentel weds chef Kathryna Yu]. ''ABS-CBN News''.</ref> During his first wedding anniversary with Yu, Pimentel announced that they were expecting their first child together.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Domingo |first1=Katrina |title=Koko Pimentel's wife Kathryna pregnant with first baby |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/10/17/19/koko-pimentels-wife-kathryna-pregnant-with-first-baby |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2020, Pimentel announced that he tested positive for the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), amid its [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|pandemic in the Philippines]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Senator Pimentel tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/25/Senator-Koko-Pimentel-coronavirus-COVID-19-test.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Earlier on March 12, multiple senators began practicing self-quarantine as a precaution against the virus, and also because one of the resource persons who attended the Senate session on March 5 tested positive for the disease.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Domingo|first1=Katrina|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/25/20/koko-pimentel-positive-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Senator Pimentel tests positive for COVID-19|date=March 25, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/spotlight/03/26/20/timeline-koko-pimentels-covid-19-crisis|title=TIMELINE: Koko Pimentel\u2019s COVID-19 crisis|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> On March 16, Senator Juan Miguel Zubiri announced that he had tested positive for COVID-19, which marked Pimentel, along with other senators, as \"patients under monitoring\" (the official designation by the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]], abbreviated as \"PUM\").<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/sites/default/files/Screening-tool-02262020.pdf|title=Decision Tool for Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Assessment (as of February 26, 2020)|last=Department of Health, Republic of the Philippines|date=2020-02-26|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> On March 18, Pimentel began to develop symptoms of the disease. Since Pimentel had developed symptoms, he was then labeled as a \"person under investigation\" (PUI). He took the COVID-19 test on March 20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-ph/news/national/a%C3%B1o-on-koko-pimentels-mmc-trip-wag-mong-i-violate-ang-quarantine-mo/ar-BB11J5Hc|title=A\u00f1o on Koko Pimentel\u2019s MMC \u2018trip\u2019: \u2018\u2018Wag mong i-violate ang quarantine mo\u2019|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731415/timeline-koko-pimentel-repeatedly-broke-quarantine-despite-symptoms-covid-19-test/story/|title=TIMELINE: Koko Pimentel repeatedly broke quarantine despite symptoms, COVID-19 test|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> At the time Pimentel confirmed his diagnosis, he had visited the [[Makati Medical Center]] to accompany his wife who was in [[Childbirth|labor]]. The Makati Medical Center issued a [[press release]] criticizing Pimentel for violating the hospital's home quarantine protocol, which required PUMs to self-isolate in order to avoid exposing health professionals and other patients to possible infection.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hallare |first1=Katrina |title=Makati Med hits COVID-19-positive Pimentel for \u2019irresponsible, reckless\u2019 actions |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248399/makati-med-hits-covid-19-positive-pimentel-for-irresponsible-reckless-actions |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248399/makati-med-hits-covid-19-positive-pimentel-for-irresponsible-reckless-actions|title=Makati Med hits COVID-19-positive Pimentel for \u2018irresponsible, reckless\u2019 actions|last=Hallare|first=Katrina|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Bureau of Investigation (Philippines)|National Bureau of Investigation]] is probing Pimentel over his possible breach of the quarantine protocols. The [[Department of Justice (Philippines)|Department of Justice]] will issue a subpoena for him regarding the breach sometime in mid-April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/1/Koko-Pimentel-NBI-investigation-quarantine-breach.html|title=NBI probes Koko Pimentel over possible quarantine breach|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1255110/doj-to-summon-pimentel-next-week-over-quarantine-breach|title=DOJ to summon Pimentel next week over quarantine breach|last=Torres-Tupas|first=Tetch|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Former dean, lawyer Rico Quicho filed a complaint against the senator for allegedly violating Republic Act No. 11332.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/07/20/doj-says-likely-to-issue-subpoena-for-koko-pimentel-next-week|title=DOJ says likely to issue subpoena for Koko Pimentel next week|website=ABS-CBN|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070310163912/http://www.inquirer.net/specialfeatures/eleksyon2007/candidates.php?name=Pimentel%2C-Aquilino-III-%28Koko%29 Aquilino Koko Pimentel's Biodata]\n*[http://kokopimentel.org/ Senator Koko Pimentel]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ph-upr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Francis Escudero]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate <br>Justice and Human Rights Committee]]|years=2013\u20132016}}\n{{S-aft|rows=2|after=[[Leila de Lima]]}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate Electoral Reforms and <br>People's Participation Committee]]|years=2013\u20132016}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leila de Lima]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate Electoral Reforms and <br>People's Participation Committee]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Imee Marcos]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Juan Miguel Zubiri]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate <br>Trade, Commerce and <br>Entrepreneurship Committee]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Loren Legarda]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[List of Philippine Senate committees|Philippine Senate <br>Foreign Relations Committee]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Franklin Drilon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Senate of the Philippines]]|years=2016\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tito Sotto]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jejomar Binay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of [[PDP\u2013Laban]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Philippine Senate Presidents}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Senatorial history of Aquilino \"Koko\" Pimentel III\n|list=\n{{15th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{16th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{17th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{18th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pimentel, Koko}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ilocano people]]\n[[Category:Filipino lawyers]]\n[[Category:People from Cagayan de Oro]]\n[[Category:PDP\u2013Laban politicians]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 18th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 17th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 16th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 15th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Ateneo de Manila University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines Diliman alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Senate of the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "Maye222", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life:reverting to original content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koko_Pimentel"}
{"title_page": "Chicago Avenue Pumping Station", "text_new": "{{short description|Pumping station}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| name               = Chicago Avenue Pumping Station\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| image              = Chicago Pumping Station Rev.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_alt          = \n| caption            = Chicago Avenue Pumping Station\n| image_map          = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n| address            = 821 North [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]]\n| city               = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n| country            = [[United States]]\n| designation        = \n| architect          = \n| owner              = [[Chicago|City of Chicago]]\n| tenant             = [[Lookingglass Theatre Company]]\n| operator           = \n| capacity           = 250\n| type               = \n| opened             = \n| reopened           = 2003\n| yearsactive        = \n| rebuilt            = \n| closed             = \n| demolished         = \n| othernames         = \n| production         = \n| currentuse         = \n| website            = {{URL|http://lookingglasstheatre.org}}\n{{Infobox NRHP \n| name =[[Chicago Water Tower|Chicago Avenue Water Tower]] and Pumping Station\n| embed = yes\n| nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes\n| area =\n| built =1869\n| added = April 23, 1975\n| governing_body = Local\n| refnum=75000644 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2006a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Image:Water tower place.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The 1869 pumping station, located across Michigan Avenue from the Water Tower.]]\n\nThe '''Chicago Avenue Pumping Station''' is a historic district contributing property in the [[Old Chicago Water Tower District]] [[landmark]] district.  It is located on [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] along the [[Magnificent Mile]] shopping district in the [[Near North Side, Chicago|Near North Side]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]], [[Illinois]].  It is on the east side of Michigan Avenue opposite the [[Chicago Water Tower]].\n\nThe [[pumping station]] was built in 1869 by architect [[William W. Boyington]]. In 1918, when [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Pine Street]] was widened, the plans were altered in order to give the [[Chicago Water Tower]] and Pumping Station a featured location.<ref name=\"wolfe\">Gerald Wolfe. ''Chicago In and Around the Loop''. McGraw-Hill, 1996. pp.233-236</ref>\n\n==Renovation==\n\n[[File:Chicago Avenue Pumping Station4.jpeg|thumb|right|200px|Inside the pumping station]]\nIn 2003 and 2004 the building was awarded several honors for [[adaptive reuse]] based on renovations which accommodated the [[Lookingglass Theatre Company]].  In fact, early in this decade four different redevelopment projects were occurring simultaneously at this landmark.  The other projects included roof deck replacement, [[fa\u00e7ade]] restoration, exterior architectural [[lighting]] improvements, [[landscaping]] improvements and [[lead paint]] abatement.  The following are the awards won for redevelopment and renovation:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hdrinc.com/13/38/1/default.aspx?projectID=408 |accessdate=May 21, 2007 |title=Chicago Avenue Pumping Station Roof Deck Replacement |publisher=HDR, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070804230525/http://www.hdrinc.com/13/38/1/default.aspx?projectID=408 |archivedate=August 4, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n*Consulting Engineers Council of Illinois, ACEC Engineering Excellence-State Level: Honor Award-Illinois, Structural Systems category, 2004\n*City of Chicago Landmarks Preservation, Chicago Landmark Award for Preservation Excellence, 2003\n*Consulting Engineers Council of Illinois, ACEC Engineering Excellence-State Level: Honor Award-Illinois, 2003\n*National Council of Structural Engineers Association, NCSEA Excellence in Structural Engineering Award - Merit Award, Building project under $5 million, 2003\n*Richard H. Driehaus Foundation - DePaul University, Richard H. Driehaus Foundation Public Innovator Award, Honorable Mention, Local, This award was for a combination of the Roof Deck Replacement and other Facility & Site Enhancements, including Exterior Architectural Lighting & Landscaping Improvements and Facade Restoration in which HDR was vitally involved, 2003\n*Structural Engineers Association (SEA), SEA Excellence in Structural Engineering Award: Overall Excellence, Best Small Structure Category, Local, Projects under $5 Million, 2003\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chicago architecture]]\n* [[Water tower]]\n* [[Water Tower Place]]\n{{commons category|Chicago Water Tower|position=left}}\n{{coord|41|53|50|N|87|37|26|W|display=title|region:US-IL_source:GNIS}}\n\n{{Chicago mtp}}\n{{Chicago}}\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicago Avenue Pumping Station}}\n[[Category:Towers in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Water supply pumping stations on the National Register of Historic Places]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1869]]\n[[Category:1869 establishments in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pumping station}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox theatre\n| name               = Chicago Avenue Pumping Station\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| image              = Chicago Pumping Station Rev.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_alt          = \n| caption            = Chicago Avenue Pumping Station\n| image_map          = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n| address            = 821 North [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]]\n| city               = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n| country            = [[United States]]\n| designation        = \n| architect          = \n| owner              = [[Chicago|City of Chicago]]\n| tenant             = [[Lookingglass Theatre Company]]\n| operator           = \n| capacity           = 250\n| type               = \n| opened             = \n| reopened           = 2003\n| yearsactive        = \n| rebuilt            = \n| closed             = \n| demolished         = \n| othernames         = \n| production         = \n| currentuse         = \n| website            = {{URL|http://lookingglasstheatre.org}}\n{{Infobox NRHP \n| name =[[Chicago Water Tower|Chicago Avenue Water Tower]] and Pumping Station\n| embed = yes\n| nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes\n| area =\n| built =1869\n| added = April 23, 1975\n| governing_body = Local\n| refnum=75000644 <ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2006a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Image:Water tower place.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The 1869 pumping station, located across Michigan Avenue from the Water Tower.]]\n\nThe '''Chicago Avenue Pumping Station''' is a historic district contributing property in the [[Old Chicago Water Tower District]] [[landmark]] district.  It is located on [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] along the [[Magnificent Mile]] shopping district in the [[Near North Side, Chicago|Near North Side]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]], [[Illinois]].  It is on the east side of Michigan Avenue opposite the [[Chicago Water Tower]].\n\nThe [[pumping station]] was built in 1869 by architect [[William W. Boyington]]. In 1918, when [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Pine Street]] was widened, the plans were altered in order to give the [[Chicago Water Tower]] and Pumping Station a featured location.<ref name=\"wolfe\">Gerald Wolfe. ''Chicago In and Around the Loop''. McGraw-Hill, 1996. pp.233-236</ref>\n\n==Renovation==\n\n[[File:Chicago Avenue Pumping Station4.jpeg|thumb|right|200px|Inside the pumping station]]\nIn 2003 and 2004 the building was awarded several honors for [[adaptive reuse]] based on renovations which accommodated the [[Lookingglass Theatre Company]].  In fact, early in this decade four different redevelopment projects were occurring simultaneously at this landmark.  The other projects included roof deck replacement, [[fa\u00e7ade]] restoration, exterior architectural [[lighting]] improvements, [[landscaping]] improvements and [[lead paint]] abatement.  The following are the awards won for redevelopment and renovation:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hdrinc.com/13/38/1/default.aspx?projectID=408 |accessdate=May 21, 2007 |title=Chicago Avenue Pumping Station Roof Deck Replacement |publisher=HDR, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070804230525/http://www.hdrinc.com/13/38/1/default.aspx?projectID=408 |archivedate=August 4, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n*Consulting Engineers Council of Illinois, ACEC Engineering Excellence-State Level: Honor Award-Illinois, Structural Systems category, 2004\n*City of Chicago Landmarks Preservation, Chicago Landmark Award for Preservation Excellence, 2003\n*Consulting Engineers Council of Illinois, ACEC Engineering Excellence-State Level: Honor Award-Illinois, 2003\n*National Council of Structural Engineers Association, NCSEA Excellence in Structural Engineering Award - Merit Award, Building project under $5 million, 2003\n*Richard H. Driehaus Foundation - DePaul University, Richard H. Driehaus Foundation Public Innovator Award, Honorable Mention, Local, This award was for a combination of the Roof Deck Replacement and other Facility & Site Enhancements, including Exterior Architectural Lighting & Landscaping Improvements and Facade Restoration in which HDR was vitally involved, 2003\n*Structural Engineers Association (SEA), SEA Excellence in Structural Engineering Award: Overall Excellence, Best Small Structure Category, Local, Projects under $5 Million, 2003\n\n==Notes=